00:02:00.790 --> 00:02:04.630
One of the key focuses is multicore capability.

00:02:04.629 --> 00:02:13.069
So to start with, we have a brand new scheduler, smart cache
and CPU management, which means you can now on the threads,

00:02:13.069 --> 00:02:20.049
basically bounce around between
different cores and blow away the CPU cache.

00:02:20.050 --> 00:02:24.090
We also have TCP input processing distributed
across multiple cores.

00:02:24.090 --> 00:02:26.530
Which means that if you have a server that's under load.

00:02:26.530 --> 00:02:28.650
It can respond much better.

00:02:30.030 --> 00:02:30.819
Thank you.

00:02:30.819 --> 00:02:34.739
( Applause )

00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:39.219
>> The use of global locks are
also needed for most system costs.

00:02:39.219 --> 00:02:43.639
Which means that you can now execute a bunch of different
stuff in parallel, and really take advantage

00:02:43.639 --> 00:02:47.709
of those extra cores, which in general
brings up the whole server performance.

00:02:47.710 --> 00:02:51.150
And the list goes on and on and on.

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:55.569
If you look at general enhancements,
we now have support for send file.

00:02:55.569 --> 00:03:00.439
