00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:19.330
So with Leopard Server what you
can do is push the preferences

00:06:19.329 --> 00:06:22.740
for the Time Machine from the center of open directory.

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:27.530
And then have all the clients back
up to a set of centralized servers.

00:06:27.529 --> 00:06:31.439
That way the IT department has a much better
control over the process of backing things up.

00:06:31.439 --> 00:06:36.899
And of course, with Xsan run out of
space just keep throwing hardware at it,

00:06:36.899 --> 00:06:40.709
and Xsan can automatically expand the volume for you.

00:06:40.709 --> 00:06:45.750
And as your company grows you can
keep adding server hardware as well.

00:06:45.750 --> 00:06:53.180
So -- and here is the workgroup manager GUI for
configuring Time Machine backup options.

00:06:54.220 --> 00:06:56.200
So that's Time Machine.

00:06:56.199 --> 00:06:58.579
Next, Spotlight server.

00:06:58.579 --> 00:07:02.819
Such -- Steve mentioned and we now have the ability

00:07:02.819 --> 00:07:07.329
to search multiple volumes just
like local volumes transparently.

00:07:07.329 --> 00:07:13.050
So if you work in a publishing work group you can
