00:07:13.050 --> 00:07:18.550
And you can use all the features of Leopard,
such as QuickLook, or the cover flow.

00:07:18.550 --> 00:07:18.920
Everything.

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:21.780
It just works automatically.

00:07:21.779 --> 00:07:25.259
Or you can also use existing features
like smart folders,

00:07:25.259 --> 00:07:30.920
so it can interpret this whole process
into your work flow for your group.

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:34.300
And on the server side, there is
no configuration there also.

00:07:34.300 --> 00:07:40.920
Just out of the box, every single shipment is
automatically indexed and able to be searchs.

00:07:40.920 --> 00:07:46.710
In this bonus, you also have a patch module that
let's you do search remotely from a Web page.

00:07:46.709 --> 00:07:52.169
So if anybody wants to come up with Spotlight front end
for iPhone there's an opportunity right there.

00:07:54.879 --> 00:07:56.659
Next up is RADIUS Server.

00:07:56.660 --> 00:07:59.260
So this is the best kept secret of Leopard Server.

00:07:59.259 --> 00:08:05.980
So anyway, this feature's great if you're
managing lots of airport base stations.

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:07.410
And here's how it works.

00:08:07.410 --> 00:08:09.990
Let's look at the university as an example.

00:08:09.990 --> 00:08:16.180
So a lot of company -- universities -- have open network
where anybody can just walk up and join the network.

00:08:16.180 --> 00:08:20.290
But I just want to protect the network and require
authentication.

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:24.310
With RADIUS feature what you can
do is point all the base stations

00:08:24.310 --> 00:08:27.769
to the authorzing Open Directory server who's RADIUS
enabled.

00:08:27.769 --> 00:08:30.889
So when students go up to the base station to

00:08:30.889 --> 00:08:34.819
or they need to authenticate, goes to Open
Directory server and they get an access.

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:40.210
The same password that they use for the mail application
when (Inaudible) out of the institutional level.

00:08:41.639 --> 00:08:46.370
And this is based on the open soucre software called
Free Radius.

00:08:47.600 --> 00:08:50.259
And we even added Setup Assistant.

00:08:50.259 --> 00:08:58.269
So all you have to do is go through four different panels
of this assistant and you can configure the whole network.

00:08:58.269 --> 00:09:00.299
We also made a change to the Server Admin.

00:09:00.299 --> 00:09:05.299
So now from within a Server Admin you can
browse and add different base stations.

00:09:05.299 --> 00:09:09.939
And the Server Admin knows to authorize on
directory talk to the base station and configure it

00:09:09.940 --> 00:09:13.100
to use radios and point to the right directive server.

00:09:14.649 --> 00:09:21.600
So if you are managing a wireless network it's
something that you want to take a look at.

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:23.370
And the last thing it the Web platform.

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:27.169
So we have clearly set up tools that
you can use for the Web development.

00:09:27.169 --> 00:09:35.949
We, of course, have all the basic stuff, such as Apache,
MySQL, PHP, all integrated, and it's all now 64-bit.

00:09:35.950 --> 00:09:39.610
And as Greg mentioned earlier, we
also have Ruby on Rails now as well

00:09:39.610 --> 00:09:44.680
as over 20 gems prebundled and all configured.

00:09:44.679 --> 00:09:47.769
So that should make life a lot easier for a lot of people.

00:09:50.169 --> 00:09:55.269
And of course have other familiar technologies, like the
Perl, Tom Cat, WebObjects, (Inaudible) as well.

00:09:55.269 --> 00:09:59.419
And again, most of these components are 64-bit now.

00:10:01.309 --> 00:10:08.659
So, you have -- we have services for everyone from small
businesses to corporations to higher educational sites.

00:10:08.659 --> 00:10:14.230
And just like desktop site, there is no standard
edition or advanced edition or small business edition.

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:18.490
All of these services are in a single package
of Mac OS X Server that you can buy

00:10:18.490 --> 00:10:22.180
and then you get to pick which services you want to use.

00:10:22.179 --> 00:10:24.339
So that's services.

00:10:24.340 --> 00:10:26.899
Now let's move on to other administration.

00:10:26.899 --> 00:10:31.500
So one of the key goals of Leopard Server
was to make it super-easy for people

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:34.899
to deploy and manage all these great services.

00:10:34.899 --> 00:10:38.949
And what we did was we kind of stepped
back and asked ourselves the questions.

00:10:38.950 --> 00:10:42.330
So for our Admins, and how are they using --

00:10:42.330 --> 00:10:46.550
what context are they using our server and
what are the issues that they are having.

00:10:46.549 --> 00:10:50.439
And we came up with three different
scenarios under which servers are being used.

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:53.120
And of course, corresponding Admin types.

00:10:53.120 --> 00:10:55.159
The first one was for small businesses.

00:10:55.159 --> 00:10:58.879
So this is a place where there
is no IT staff that's educated.

00:10:58.879 --> 00:11:03.980
So whoever happens to know the most about the
computer, the computer guy needs to be at Admin.

00:11:03.980 --> 00:11:07.070
And what he or she does is go out and buy some books.

00:11:07.070 --> 00:11:07.220
( Laughter )

00:11:07.220 --> 00:11:13.769
>> And try best to set up server and
configure all the client's user server.

00:11:13.769 --> 00:11:16.259
Kind of scary.

00:11:16.259 --> 00:11:22.350
And -- but all they want to do is just set up
all the basic services without much tweaking.

00:11:22.350 --> 00:11:23.820
Just the basic settings.

00:11:23.820 --> 00:11:27.930
And once it's configured, they will hardly
ever touch on the unless they need to add new users

00:11:27.929 --> 00:11:31.370
or do something unless they absolutely have to.

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:35.590
So the first challenge, really,
was to help out these people.

00:11:35.590 --> 00:11:42.320
The next step was department of service,
within institutions and corporations.

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:48.530
So a lot of people do want to deploy their servers
independent of what's provided by the IT staff.

00:11:48.529 --> 00:11:54.209
For example, you might have the departmental web
site, or the HR department may have their own file server

00:11:54.210 --> 00:11:58.060
to keep confidential information and so on.

00:11:58.059 --> 00:12:02.079
And typically, just configure maybe
one specific service, or maybe two.

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:04.480
Not a whole bunch of different stuff.

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:07.470
But one thing they do want to do is they want to integrate

00:12:07.470 --> 00:12:11.600
with the direct infrastructure that's provided
by the institution or the corporation.

00:12:11.600 --> 00:12:16.800
So you have the single user password and
you have to manage separate user accounts.

00:12:17.830 --> 00:12:21.340
But it's often difficult to do that for a lot of people.

00:12:21.340 --> 00:12:27.070
So typically what ends up happening is
either they create separate users and groups,

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:30.060
try to manage it, an then quickly become out dated.

00:12:30.059 --> 00:12:36.569
Or they call the IT staff for help and they have to come out
and set up the server for them, set up the clients for them,

00:12:36.570 --> 00:12:39.530
bind them to the server, introductory server and so on.

00:12:39.529 --> 00:12:43.419
So extra work that gets created for the IT staff.

00:12:43.419 --> 00:12:48.969
So for these people our goal was to really come
up -- again -- real easy way to deploy the server,

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:53.870
but integrate it into the infrastructure that's
provided by the corporation or institution.

00:12:53.870 --> 00:12:57.519
And we off load the extra work from the IT staff.

00:13:00.990 --> 00:13:05.570
Then the third one is just basically
the rest of administrators out there.

00:13:05.570 --> 00:13:10.020
We want to advance people who want to specialize
deployment, or just want to use advanced tools.

00:13:10.019 --> 00:13:13.559
Probably a lot of people in this
audience fall into this category.

00:13:13.559 --> 00:13:16.679
So these are people who know what they are
talking about, and they know what they are doing.

00:13:16.679 --> 00:13:20.659
They know what IPP stands for; what IPFW stands for.

00:13:20.659 --> 00:13:23.449
And they read the writing books
for fun before they go to bed --

00:13:23.450 --> 00:13:26.620
( Laughter )
>> -- and other stuff.

00:13:26.620 --> 00:13:30.500
And so we've been talking most directly and
indirectly, quite a lot of different feed back.

00:13:30.500 --> 00:13:32.629
And we've got a lot of good ones.

00:13:32.629 --> 00:13:37.480
But in particular, a lot of them on it have the
ability to better manage a large number of servers.

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:39.830
The tools we have today is not really scaleable.

00:13:39.830 --> 00:13:43.320
So that's one of the biggest feed back.

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:49.830
So we took all these ideas and feed back and went off and
did some engineering work and came up with a few things.

00:13:49.830 --> 00:13:52.889
The first thing we did was stream line the server system.

00:13:52.889 --> 00:13:55.240
The server set up application.

00:13:55.240 --> 00:14:01.480
So now when you launch it, the first thing it's going
to ask you is to pick one of the three concentrations,

00:14:01.480 --> 00:14:08.060
either standard, work group, or advanced, which
maps to those scenarios that we talked about.

00:14:08.059 --> 00:14:11.779
And then if you pick standard we
will try to do everything for you.

00:14:11.779 --> 00:14:12.980
All right.

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:14.710
So you don't have to set up anything.

00:14:14.710 --> 00:14:20.860
For example, if you have a configuration like this and
it's an Airport base station router, we talk to it directly

00:14:20.860 --> 00:14:26.490
and then all configure not port forwarding, so
things like iChat Server Federation or mail server,

00:14:26.490 --> 00:14:31.190
or anything that goes out to the Internet
just works, without any further configuration.

00:14:31.190 --> 00:14:34.020
( Applause )

00:14:34.019 --> 00:14:35.759
>> And it is all in Server.

00:14:35.759 --> 00:14:38.710
All in one server configuration that's preconfigured

00:14:38.710 --> 00:14:43.950
and enabling all the key productivity
and corroboration services.

00:14:43.950 --> 00:14:52.400
And we will include the VPN server, so even the small
business employees can work even after they go home.

00:14:52.399 --> 00:14:54.529
( Applause )
>> Next, worker configuration.

00:14:54.529 --> 00:15:00.039
So if you pick this configuration it's
really for the department servers.

00:15:00.039 --> 00:15:00.829
Here's an example.

00:15:00.830 --> 00:15:03.000
At Alpo (assumed spelling), we
have centralized director server

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:07.320
and different departments have all
their servers managed by themselves.

00:15:07.320 --> 00:15:09.210
And this one really cool feature called easy Kerberos.

00:15:09.210 --> 00:15:18.050
What this does is if you select worker configuration, and
if that open directory server is also a Leopard Server,

00:15:18.049 --> 00:15:24.839
we do some magic underneath it, and we automatically
Kerberize all the services on that departmental server.

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:27.970
And without any IT involvement in this at all,

00:15:27.970 --> 00:15:32.149
which means anybody in the department can easily
manage, deploy these servers and manage it.

00:15:32.149 --> 00:15:36.269
And also there's a benefit to the clients, which
is if all this department's servers are pointing

00:15:36.269 --> 00:15:40.679
to the service directory, all the clients can
take advantage of single signing programs.

00:15:40.679 --> 00:15:44.379
So they won't have all different passwords
for different departmental servers.

00:15:44.379 --> 00:15:50.669
So that's some of the cool things we did here.

00:15:50.669 --> 00:15:55.059
And here are the services that's
enabled for the worker configuration.

00:15:57.429 --> 00:16:00.939
Now, once the server's set up, you need to manage it.

00:16:00.940 --> 00:16:05.180
Adding new users, maybe tweaking the
Spam filtering, sensitivity, and so on.

00:16:05.179 --> 00:16:09.359
So we looked at and see how can we make
work book manager and server much easier

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:12.690
to use without penalizing advanced people.

00:16:12.690 --> 00:16:14.810
And we reached the conclusion that we cannot.

00:16:14.809 --> 00:16:18.959
So what we did was we created a brand
new application that's really optimized

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:23.150
for the basic usage for those novice Admins.

