00:49:07.889 --> 00:49:10.449
These all interoperate.

00:49:10.449 --> 00:49:11.730
There's no competing standards here.

00:49:11.730 --> 00:49:14.690
It's all of the C technology.

00:49:14.690 --> 00:49:19.670
And then we have system imaging.

00:49:19.670 --> 00:49:24.990
System imaging -- System Image Utility has a sordid history.

00:49:24.989 --> 00:49:29.949
So I threw it away.

00:49:29.949 --> 00:49:33.819
And built a brand new system of image utility.

00:49:33.820 --> 00:49:41.630
( Applause )

00:49:41.630 --> 00:49:44.550
>> There are two users that we
see for the System Image Utility.

00:49:44.550 --> 00:49:46.680
The beginner user, or the basic user.

00:49:46.679 --> 00:49:49.859
The person who wants to get in and
get out, and just build an image.

00:49:49.860 --> 00:49:50.880
So sort of a wizard work flow.

00:49:50.880 --> 00:49:51.950
You get in, you get out.

00:49:51.949 --> 00:49:56.460
Then we use the Automator technology
to allow you to allow you to develop work flows

00:49:56.460 --> 00:50:00.019
to actually allow you to build more complex images.

00:50:00.019 --> 00:50:02.090
It's just like building a work flow inside of Automator.

00:50:02.090 --> 00:50:04.390
So we'll be talking more about this later this week.

00:50:04.389 --> 00:50:08.619
The other thing we did inside of NetBoot
is actually give you status back

00:50:08.619 --> 00:50:10.650
for the images you're installing inside of Admin.

