00:52:51.739 --> 00:52:53.309
Let's talk about iCal server.

00:52:53.309 --> 00:52:55.920
We talked about -- we brought this in last year.

00:52:55.920 --> 00:52:57.610
And we've been working on it for another year.

00:52:57.610 --> 00:52:59.380
And it's -- sweet.

00:52:59.380 --> 00:53:04.030
I want to talk a little bit about what our goal is here.

00:53:04.030 --> 00:53:07.620
And I want to talk about it from the Microsoft perspective.

00:53:07.619 --> 00:53:12.109
Which -- in the Microsoft world with calendaring
you've got exchange server in the middle.

00:53:12.110 --> 00:53:16.780
And if you want to use -- if you want to use
a client you've got Outlook for your desktop.

00:53:16.780 --> 00:53:18.200
You've got out look for the Web.

00:53:18.199 --> 00:53:20.259
You've got Outlook for phones.

00:53:20.260 --> 00:53:22.500
This is terrific.

00:53:22.500 --> 00:53:23.460
If you want to use Outlook.

00:53:23.460 --> 00:53:24.590
( Laughter )

00:53:24.590 --> 00:53:28.690
>> I don't want to use Outlook.

00:53:28.690 --> 00:53:31.900
So, this is how we view it from an iCal server world.

00:53:31.900 --> 00:53:33.269
You've got iCal server in the middle.

00:53:33.269 --> 00:53:38.119
And if you want to use iCal, which
is what I use, you can use it.

00:53:38.119 --> 00:53:44.190
But if you want to use Mozilla's Sunbird, or Mozilla's
Lightening Extension as part of Sunbird -- is that right?

00:53:44.190 --> 00:53:46.159
Whatever. You can do that.

00:53:46.159 --> 00:53:48.769
If you want to use Outlook, you can.

00:53:48.769 --> 00:53:50.300
And I'll tell you about that in a second.

00:53:50.300 --> 00:53:53.890
Or you can use a Web-based browser.

00:53:53.889 --> 00:54:00.920
Or -- this isn't an Apple product, this is Marware's
project X. They're actually using it for project management.

00:54:00.920 --> 00:54:01.780
Project management?

00:54:01.780 --> 00:54:02.340
Calendar server?

00:54:02.340 --> 00:54:03.789
What's going on here?

00:54:03.789 --> 00:54:06.230
Think about what project management software needs?

00:54:06.230 --> 00:54:07.119
It's got people.

00:54:07.119 --> 00:54:09.469
It's got events, it's got time.

00:54:09.469 --> 00:54:13.799
This sounds like something that
you want in a calendaring system.

00:54:13.800 --> 00:54:17.970
What they're using is they're using iCal
server as a repository for their information.

00:54:17.969 --> 00:54:22.819
And this is a great proof point to show what you
get when you build a server on open standards.

00:54:22.820 --> 00:54:24.990
Think of the other applications that can be developed

00:54:24.989 --> 00:54:29.099
when there's no longer this big black
wall around your calendaring information.

00:54:29.099 --> 00:54:32.909
That's you get with Exchange server, not with iCal server.

00:54:32.909 --> 00:54:37.389
We get this because we're built on CalDAV.

00:54:37.389 --> 00:54:43.109
This is a standard that we've been working with
-- a company -- organization called CalConnect.

00:54:43.110 --> 00:54:45.120
And I'll talk about them in a second.

00:54:45.119 --> 00:54:48.960
What we liked about CalDAV, and we
said this last year, is that it's --

00:54:48.960 --> 00:54:52.150
first off we wanted to see wide-spread vendor support.

00:54:52.150 --> 00:54:55.660
But it also doesn't necessarily reinvent all of the wheel.

00:54:55.659 --> 00:54:57.960
Just a protocol stack that it builds up CalDAV.

00:54:57.960 --> 00:55:01.010
Now at the bottom there's HTTP.
Which we're all familiar with.

00:55:01.010 --> 00:55:03.780
And you've got WebDAV, which has been around a while.

00:55:03.780 --> 00:55:06.100
And you've got iCalendar, we use for our accounting file.

00:55:06.099 --> 00:55:07.599
That's an existing standards.

00:55:07.599 --> 00:55:11.170
On top of that still in purple we've got iTip,
which we use for notifications.

00:55:11.170 --> 00:55:13.750
And then on top of that we've got CalDAV.

00:55:13.750 --> 00:55:17.969
CalDAV is a basically WebDAV extensions
for all the scheduling that you need to do.

00:55:17.969 --> 00:55:19.689
Reoccurrence, read busy reports.

00:55:19.690 --> 00:55:21.420
Stuff like that.

00:55:21.420 --> 00:55:22.389
All the purple's done.

00:55:22.389 --> 00:55:22.969
It's been there.

00:55:22.969 --> 00:55:23.669
We're using it.

00:55:23.670 --> 00:55:27.860
We don't have anything new out, but it's doing CalDAV.

00:55:27.860 --> 00:55:31.099
So -- so we're working really closely
with the CalConnect folks.

00:55:31.099 --> 00:55:34.420
I'm really happy, as you'll see in
a demo here in a second, with iCal.

00:55:34.420 --> 00:55:40.280
I really believe that iCal server and iCal is by far the
furtherest along in terms of adopting these standards.

00:55:40.280 --> 00:55:43.960
But there's lots of room for everyone to get involved.

00:55:43.960 --> 00:55:47.980
This is the kitchen sink slide while
I tell you that what you're getting

00:55:47.980 --> 00:55:51.719
with iCal server is a featured
competitive solution with an exchange.

00:55:51.719 --> 00:55:55.230
I am not going to read all these features, but I
want you to know is we're using this at Apple now.

00:55:55.230 --> 00:55:58.940
We've got several large engineering
organizations actually on iCal server.

00:55:58.940 --> 00:56:02.889
And that's a testimony to being
a really rich-featured product.

00:56:02.889 --> 00:56:04.000
It also scales nicely.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:06.389
It's got to if they use it at Apple.

00:56:06.389 --> 00:56:12.039
Whether you're just using it as a single server or as you
grow and you add more servers, or you add DNS,

00:56:12.039 --> 00:56:17.809
you add more servers, then you put Xsan you're
buying a lot of hardware, this makes us really happy.

00:56:17.809 --> 00:56:21.829
ICal server does a really good
job of scaling and performing.

00:56:21.829 --> 00:56:23.090
So enough of me.

00:56:23.090 --> 00:56:26.570
What I would like to do is actually
show you iCal and iCal server.

00:56:26.570 --> 00:56:30.240
We've got will Wilfredo Sanchez from the Calendaring team.

00:56:30.239 --> 00:56:38.250
( Applause )

00:56:38.250 --> 00:56:40.289
>> You hear me now?

00:56:40.289 --> 00:56:40.779
Here we go.

00:56:40.780 --> 00:56:46.130
Okay. So as with many server things, the best
way to show it to you is to start with a client.

00:56:46.130 --> 00:56:48.430
So we're going to show you iCal here.

00:56:48.429 --> 00:56:49.750
Let's get that launched up.

00:56:49.750 --> 00:56:54.400
And as with Tiger, you can have
local calendar information here.

00:56:54.400 --> 00:57:01.410
You can see I go to Tommy's every Monday for tequila,
watch TV, and I'm going to Bourbon and Branch later in the week.

00:57:01.409 --> 00:57:05.190
But up in this middle area, this is all
blanked out because this is my work time.

00:57:05.190 --> 00:57:07.650
And really what I want here is my work calendar.

00:57:07.650 --> 00:57:11.889
And my work calendar I need a much richer
sort of interactive environment here.

00:57:11.889 --> 00:57:14.690
So why don't I just go up and bring up iCal preferences.

00:57:14.690 --> 00:57:18.750
And as you can see there's a new accounts tab up here.

00:57:18.750 --> 00:57:21.360
And I'm going create an account.

00:57:21.360 --> 00:57:25.530
Just be unimaginative and call it server calendar.

00:57:29.500 --> 00:57:33.550
Enter my user name and my password.

00:57:33.550 --> 00:57:36.960
And notice that there's some information
-- room here for some server information.

00:57:36.960 --> 00:57:40.780
But I am not going to bother with that, because iCal
speaks to open directory, as it's actually going to look

00:57:40.780 --> 00:57:43.320
up that information based on the user name I gave it.

00:57:43.320 --> 00:57:48.000
And sure enough, when I get this out of the way you can see
that now all of a sudden I've got some information up here.

00:57:48.000 --> 00:57:51.039
Now if I were a brand new user to
this, you would see a clean slate.

00:57:51.039 --> 00:57:54.610
Because I've use this at work and
I've already schedule some meetings,

00:57:54.610 --> 00:57:58.890
I'm pretty booked up for lunch this week
and I've got a team meeting on Tuesday.

00:57:58.889 --> 00:58:01.789
Now let's set up a theoretical situation.

00:58:01.789 --> 00:58:05.800
Let's say I just buy an expensive house in
San Francisco, you all know they're not cheap.

00:58:05.800 --> 00:58:08.570
And I work for this guy named Michael who you just met.

00:58:08.570 --> 00:58:11.000
And I want a big fat raise.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:13.519
So I am going to set up a meeting with Michael.

00:58:13.519 --> 00:58:16.579
I am going to select the calendar
I want to schedule it against.

00:58:16.579 --> 00:58:19.769
Set up time for some coffee.

00:58:19.769 --> 00:58:22.809
So it's -- edit this event.

00:58:22.809 --> 00:58:23.869
Call this coffee.

00:58:23.869 --> 00:58:27.460
Won't really make a mention of
the whole raise thing just yet.

00:58:27.460 --> 00:58:32.670
Now if I were using Tiger, you know,
like, I'd call him up and say hey Michael,

00:58:32.670 --> 00:58:35.889
you've got any time 10 o'clock tomorrow,
can you block that out on your schedule?

00:58:35.889 --> 00:58:37.359
I've got it on mine.

00:58:37.360 --> 00:58:38.539
But that's like, so Tiger.

00:58:38.539 --> 00:58:39.289
( Laughter )

00:58:39.289 --> 00:58:43.309
>> And we want to use something cooler.

00:58:43.309 --> 00:58:49.500
So I'm going to go to the attendees field here
and I'm going start typing in Michael's name.

00:58:49.500 --> 00:58:53.849
And you can see, again, using opportunity
directory, iCal's finding his information.

00:58:53.849 --> 00:58:57.099
And hit return.

00:58:57.099 --> 00:59:00.380
And let's see if he's available.

00:59:00.380 --> 00:59:08.680
So I can see -- oh, I actually started
at 9 a.m. here's a head's up view.

00:59:08.679 --> 00:59:11.429
The gray areas here indicate that he's not in the office.

00:59:11.429 --> 00:59:12.980
And obviously I am not either.

00:59:12.980 --> 00:59:16.230
If there were 12 people in the meeting,
obviously, this would be a taller stack.

00:59:16.230 --> 00:59:18.750
He's kind of busy at 10.

00:59:18.750 --> 00:59:22.110
9 a.m. -- I'm a slacker, I don't want to get up that early.

00:59:22.110 --> 00:59:23.970
So let's try tomorrow.

00:59:23.969 --> 00:59:25.189
Looks he's free then.

00:59:25.190 --> 00:59:27.150
So let's go ahead and book that.

00:59:27.150 --> 00:59:31.230
I'm going send him this invitation
and send him this dialogue.

00:59:31.230 --> 00:59:33.460
So there you go; I've scheduled a meeting with Michael.

00:59:33.460 --> 00:59:39.780
( Applause )

00:59:39.780 --> 00:59:42.460
>> Let's go ahead and switch users here.

00:59:42.460 --> 00:59:43.920
Let's say that I'm now -- I'm Michael.

00:59:43.920 --> 00:59:45.539
And here's my calendar.

00:59:45.539 --> 00:59:47.820
You see a much busier schedule than mine.

00:59:47.820 --> 00:59:51.890
But -- let's see what's going on.

00:59:51.889 --> 00:59:56.159
And sure enough here's a notification
for an invitation to go have some coffee.

00:59:56.159 --> 00:59:57.339
Michael likes coffee.

00:59:57.340 --> 00:59:58.809
He's got some free time.

00:59:58.809 --> 01:00:00.570
He replies, and now it's on his calendar.

01:00:00.570 --> 01:00:01.610
And viola.

01:00:01.610 --> 01:00:03.530
That's how you schedule meetings using iCal in Leopard.

01:00:03.530 --> 01:00:03.930
( Applause )

